  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3b0c-55b9-74a2-b03b-2403481b4e89\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The parse-time timezone bug is `crime_00007`, `timezone_unsafe_parse`, in `src/date.ts`.\\n\\nThe literal responsible for the promo opening a day early is:\\n\\n```ts\\n\\\"2026-12-20\\\"\\n```\\n\\nA date-only string is parsed as a calendar date at UTC midnight by JS, so in European/local-time comparisons it can land on the previous local day depending on how the rest of the code compares dates.\\n\\nSmallest change, without renaming the function: make the intended timezone explicit so production parses it the same way CI does. If CI’s UTC behaviour is the contract, change:\\n\\n```ts\\nnew Date(\\\"2026-12-20\\\")\\n```\\n\\nto:\\n\\n```ts\\nnew Date(\\\"2026-12-20T00:00:00Z\\\")\\n```\\n\\nThat pins the promo start to midnight UTC instead of letting host timezone/date parsing semantics leak into the business rule.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":26089,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":218,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":30}}\n",
